<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[578,1855,717,1081]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
In the original description this species, recently described from Guizhou (
<bibRefCitation author="Zhou X. &amp; Zhou W. - b." journalOrPublisher="Wuyi Science Journal" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" pagination="13 - 21" part="21" refId="ref4593" refString="Zhou X. &amp; Zhou W. - b. 2005. A new species of the Indolestes from Guizhou Province of China (Odonata: Lestidae). Wuyi Science Journal 21: 13 - 21." title="A new species of the Indolestes from Guizhou Province of China (Odonata: Lestidae)" type="journal article" year="2005">
Zhou &amp; Zhou 
<date box="[580,657,765,794]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="2005">2005</date>
</bibRefCitation>
), was compared to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Ris" baseAuthorityYear="1916" box="[954,1084,767,794]" class="Insecta" family="Lestidae" genus="Indolestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis box="[954,1084,767,794]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">I. gracilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but not to 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1250,1263,767,794]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">I.</emphasis>
peregrinus and 
<emphasis box="[1514,1527,767,794]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">I.</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1538,1684,767,794]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">birmanus,</emphasis>
that would be more reasonable geogra p hically. S9 was described and shown to be entirely black (
<figureCitation box="[588,730,861,890]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="3.[581,674,1708,1737]" captionTargetBox="[598,1834,1134,1658]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 3. Indolestesguizhouensis ♂ as illustrated in literature - a. S8-S10, lateral; anal appendages b. lateral, c. dorsal. — after Zhou &amp; Zhou (2005: figs. 4, 5). Not to scale ." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3358802/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Figure 3a</figureCitation>
) as in 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[831,1002,863,890]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[831,845,863,890]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">I.</emphasis>
birmanus.
</emphasis>
The schematic original figures (Figure b, c) do not show well the paraproct shape, while the cerci are shown to have so long proximal part that the inner spine is situated proximally to the middle of their length (distally in other 
<emphasis box="[580,692,1004,1033]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">species</emphasis>
of the group considered). To clarify the taxonomic 
<emphasis box="[1493,1613,1004,1033]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">position</emphasis>
of these specimens, their reexamination of photographs are necessary
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
